<===> README.md
Most of the same behavior tested for `calc()` applies to `pow()`, but for
terseness' sake isn't tested explicitly.

<===>
================================================================================
<===> positive/input.scss
a {b: pow(10, 10)}

<===> positive/output.css
a {
  b: 10000000000;
}

<===>
================================================================================
<===> base/negative/input.scss
a {b: pow(-10, 10)}

<===> base/negative/output.css
a {
  b: 10000000000;
}

<===>
================================================================================
<===> exponent/negative/input.scss
a {b: pow(10, -10)}

<===> exponent/negative/output.css
a {
  b: 0.0000000001;
}

<===>
================================================================================
<===> zeros/input.scss
a {b: pow(0, 0)}

<===> zeros/output.css
a {
  b: 1;
}

<===>
================================================================================
<===> operation/y_infinity/positive/input.scss
a {b: pow(infinity, 10)}

<===> operation/y_infinity/positive/output.css
a {
  b: calc(infinity);
}

<===>
================================================================================
<===> operation/x_infinity/positive/input.scss
a {b: pow(10, infinity)}

<===> operation/x_infinity/positive/output.css
a {
  b: calc(infinity);
}

<===>
================================================================================
<===> operation/simplification/input.scss
a {b: pow(3px - 1px + var(--c), 4px + 10px)}

<===> operation/simplification/output.css
